{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DCnz5TRaP2g5cVSLYDYkQf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Elasticsearch has HTTP SSL enabled (`xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: true`), so port 9200 only responds to HTTPS. The service is named `https` port 9200. But the auth-checker readiness probe uses `http://` (not `https://`). This is a problem.\n\nLet me look at the auth-checker spec again more carefully:\n\n```\n\"readinessProbe\": {\n    \"exec\": {\n      \"command\": [\n        \"/bin/sh\",\n        \"-c\",\n        \"curl -s --max-time 5 -u elastic:${ELASTIC_PASSWORD} \\\\\\n  http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/_security/_authenticate \\\\\\n  | grep -q '\\\"username\\\":\\\"elastic\\\"'\\n\"\n```\n\nThe readiness probe is using `http://` but the service port is labeled `https`. The port name is just a convention though—the service doesn't do SSL termination, it just forwards TCP traffic directly to port 9200 on the pods. Since the pods only accept HTTPS connections, sending an HTTP request to the service will fail.\n\nLooking at the services, both `es-headless` and `es-http` expose port 9200, but Elasticsearch only responds to HTTPS on that port. The auth-checker probe is likely misconfigured with an HTTP URL when it should be using HTTPS, which is probably what's preventing it from becoming healthy.\n\nActually, thinking about this differently—the auth-checker deployment was just created as part of the scenario setup, so it's using the old password from the secret and has never been ready. I should check if there's a working curl test or another way to verify the authentication is actually functioning.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":835,"cache_read_input_tokens":33638,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":835},"output_tokens":35,"service_tier":"stan